    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait sorry, what do you mean by \"goblin tax\"? is that a real thing in canadian real estate? i'm getting a bit confused by the metaphors.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, no worries at all! The \"goblin tax\" isn't a real thing in Canadian real estate, nor does the government actually charge goblins for anything (though I suspect they might be secretly trying to collect one from the goblins living in the basement of every new condo in Toronto). It was just a metaphor to describe the risk of losing money or getting stuck with a bad deal if the transaction goes wrong without proper safeguards.\n\nIn reality, the money you put into that escrow account isn't a tax; it's just your earnest money, held in trust by a lawyer or title company until the deal closes. Think of it like a goblin hoarding shiny coins in a jar until you promise to give them the map to the treasure chest. If you break your promise, the goblin keeps the coins. If you follow the rules, the coins are released to the seller, and the goblin gets sent back to the goblin hole to do something else.\n\nSo, while the goblin tax is definitely a fictional concept, the escrow account itself is a very real and necessary part of buying a home in Ontario. It protects both you and the seller from the chaos that would happen if the goblin tried to",
      "source": "target",
